Breast Cancer Survival Prediction Project

This project predicts breast cancer patient survival status (Alive or Dead) using clinical, demographic, and tumor characteristics. The notebook implements a full supervised machine learning workflow, including data cleaning, preprocessing, model training, evaluation, and feature analysis. The code is written in Python using pandas, scikit-learn, matplotlib, and seaborn.

-----

Project Overview

The goal of this project is to predict patient survival accurately by leveraging clinical, demographic, and tumor features. The workflow covers:

Data Cleaning
- Dropped the Survival Months column to prevent target leakage.
- Verified no missing values in the dataset.

Preprocessing
- Mapped ordinal and binary variables to numeric values.
- One-hot encoded nominal variables: Race and Marital Status.
- Scaled numeric features using StandardScaler (optional for tree-based models).

Modeling
- Random Forest Classifier with tuned hyperparameters:
  - n_estimators=300
  - max_depth=5
  - min_samples_split=5
  - min_samples_leaf=4
  - max_features='sqrt'
  - class_weight='balanced'
- Train/test split: 80/20
- Model evaluation using Accuracy, ROC-AUC, Precision-Recall, and feature importance.

Evaluation
- Metrics computed for test set:
  - Accuracy
  - ROC-AUC
- Additional evaluations:
  - Classification report (precision, recall, F1-score for Alive/Dead)
  - Feature importance ranking (top predictors: Reginol Node Positive, N Stage, 6th Stage, Age, Progesterone Status)
  - ROC Curve and Precision-Recall Curve for minority class assessment.

